metadata.name: Truchet Towers #224
metadata.description:
Curved Truchet tiling is laid down on a 3D plane forming an imaginary landscape of ripples.

The longest continuous line created by the tiling is removed, cutting a path through the terrain.
This occurs within 3D space and may or may not appear within the confines of the canvas frame,
but most likely will appear.

A tower rises up to wherever a circle is created by the tiling. Driven by the random
tiling, zero or several of these may appear within the frame. Shadows differ in each mint.

In addition to working on decorative tiling, S√©bastien Truchet worked on canals and sundials,
forming the inspiration for the exploration of shade and shadow in this work.

Mints will have a variety of earth-tone background colors with each perspective of the scene
slightly different to produce diverse results.

As I researched S√©bastien Truchet I learned that he worked with hydraulics and canal design,
as well as sundials. This became the inspiration for my new shading and shadowing technique used
in this piece.

For me this piece evokes a sense of agriculture, and connects me to an imaginary
landscape that could have looked familiar to Truchet in 18th century France.

This work was created with my own javascript, utilizing my polyline path helper library I
maintain at https://github.com/markroland/path-helper.

metadata.name: partition() #40
metadata.description:
This token continuously partitions the canvas, sometimes taking minutes to create tens of thousands of subdivisions. Each token has unique properties that govern partition number and shape, and a random chance to freeze a partition. This allows for a wide variety of outputs, all driven by pure randomness.

Properties describe the entropy of the final output, the final number of partitions, and a rare small chance for filled partitions. This token also has a few interactive features as well (see below).

Software | p5.js
Created  | 11/30/21
Artist   | nicthib

Controls:
1-9: Displays the construction of the piece at each iteration
p: Save a png of the current canvas
s: Save an svg of the current canvas (Note: this can break the live sketch, so reload the page if you want to interact further)
Space: Resets animation
Scroll, click/drag: zoom/pan

metadata.name: Plottable Mountain Moons #37
metadata.description:
What makes this NFT have value? not only the digital is cool but it is the recipe to a plottable. Owning this NFT confers the right to request a physical plot (21cm square). @greweb will ask extra fees for this service => https://greweb.me/plots/nft

Full article: https://greweb.me/2021/12/plottable-mountain-moons

Plottable Mountain Moons generalize many explorations done this year. There are 13 inks, 9 different shape primitives with recursion, various intensity, and frequencies of noise,... and many rare cases to discover!

Digital and Physical art, hybrid and decoupled:
- The art is published via a digital NFT on Tezos blockchain ‚Äì its digital representation simulates fountain pen inks drawing on paper with animated effects.
- Token to the physical world: owning each NFT confer the power to request the related physical plot: https://greweb.me/plots/nft

@greweb ‚Äì 2021 ‚Äì tech: WebGL + Rust + WASM ‚Äì CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

metadata.name: Euphonic #1069
metadata.description:
Euphonic is an exploration of the emergent visual properties that arise from placing layers of simple lines atop one another.

In general this effect is called the Moir√© effect. This effect really feels best in the tactile - when you have a printed page and an acetate sheet. This piece attempts to recreate that tactile joy.

This is built in WebGL 2 and so doesn't work in Safari 14 and below. All latest browsers will work as expected.

Licensing: BY-NC-ND see license.md for details.

metadata.name: pang #92
metadata.description:
Within each of us resides an evolutionary history of primal emotions, yet we often spend our lives dulling and controlling these instincts rather than reveling in them. Art is one of the ways we best express those instincts and intuitions ‚Äì accessing and visualizing their visceral qualities, and releasing our deepest emotions in a way we can share.

pang reflects emotions that take control of our impulses ‚Äì anguish, euphoria, obsession. By using crayon-like marks, the artworks convey the catharsis felt while drawing with a childlike abandon. To capture what gives such marks true feeling, the works deliberate the intrinsic movements, pressures, and angles shaped by hands in various moods. These qualities and their frenetic meanderings represent the infinite possibilities of where the crayon could go next ‚Äì if only we could free ourselves from the layers of control we've built.

The contradictions we struggle with are reflected throughout the works:  in the long, methodical, and mathematical path to creation that yields work that looks fast, free and unrehearsed;  through the randomly-informed computer generation of art that feels human;  and by the depiction of long-standing traditional techniques to help display the conceptual range of a young, innovative art movement still establishing its pivotal place in the canon of art. These tensions parallel the work's underlying concept, accentuating the suspicion that a learned fear of emotional expression might just be the source of our own pang. 

Created in p5.js, pang is inspired by the emotional works and processes of later abstract expressionists such as Cy Twombly and Joan Mitchell ‚Äì as well as contemporary artists like Jos√© Parla.

Functionality: 
Press ‚Äòp‚Äô to save as a png. 
Press ‚Äòb‚Äô to render with (or without) a transparent background.
Press 0-9 to render at varying degrees of quality.  0 (lowest quality) to 9 (highest quality, 15000 pixels lengthwise).
Press ‚¨ÜÔ∏è (arrow up) to incrementally increase pixel density.
Press ‚¨áÔ∏è (arrow down) to incrementally decrease pixel density.

__________
TENDER x abstractment
April 2022

metadata.name: Endless Braids #60
metadata.description:
This generative braid artwork is built in plain JavaScript, and is based on code I wrote several years ago, here updated with new aesthetics and features. This work is motivated by a beautiful mathematical structure called a braid group.

Each unique mint of the token chooses randomized parameters with varying probability weights for the number of strings, their spacing, coloring schemes and resulting color palettes, and crossing sizes, angles and frequency.

Colors are randomly generated from an algorithm, including the background color. Most of the pieces (70% probability) will feature colors from two separate hue intervals; a smaller number (20%) use only one color interval, and even more rare are the Black-White-Color palettes (6%), and the Black-and-White palette (4%).

Most of them scroll up, but approximately 7% of them scroll down.

The braid will endlessly scroll without any repetition in its pattern.

Dan Gries
Twitter: @rectangleworld

metadata.name: The beauty of imperfection #128
metadata.description:
Drawing shapes repeatedly, spinning and rotating. I use basic shapes like square, rectangle, and triangle to create this art. Regular shapes are perfect but it's a little bit boring, so I make them imperfect, just like "hand drawing". I also tried to make this generative art great for physical print, so that I can hang it on the wall. Here we go.

5 background colors:
Black, White, Blue, Green, and Red

Press ‚Äúspace‚Äù to play animation.
Press ‚Äús‚Äù to save.

Made with p5js.
Created by Costa C. | OneRocket.nft
